subSection.paragraph:
The arachidonic acid cascade in the cyclooxygenase-2 (COX-2) pathway is one of the most important pathways in the inflammatory process, in which COX-2 is a significant target for the discovery of many undescribed nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs) (
Qin et al., 2020
). To date, several drugs targeting COX-2 are on the market, such as nimesulide, meloxicam, and celecoxib. However, many drugs have numerous side effects. Consequently, searching for undescribed COX-2 inhibitors with little or no side effects is necessary.

Twelve known compounds were identified as biyoulactones A and B (
6
and 
7
) (
Tanaka et al., 2011
), quercetin 3-(6 
′′
-O-caffeoyl)-β-3-D-galactoside (
8
) (
Isaza et al., 2001
), 3,8 
′′
-bisapigenin (
9
) (
Jiang et al., 2015
), quercetn-3-O-α- L-rhamnoside (
10
) (
Jiang et al., 2015
), taxifoline-3-O-rhamnoside (
11
) (
Goetz et al., 1999
), catechol (
12
) (
Sheng et al., 2019
), 2-hydroxy-4,6-dimethoxyacetophenone (
13
) (
Hu et al., 2011
), 1,5-dihydroxy-2-(2-methylbutanoyl)-3-methoxy-6-methylbenzene (
14
) (
Wang et al., 2010
), 1,5-dihydroxy-2-(20-methylpropionyl)-3-methoxy-6-methylbenzene (
15
) (
Winnie and Simon, 2006
), and aspidinol D (
16
) (
Winnie and Simon, 2006
) by comparison of their spectroscopic and physical data with those of related literature.

In this work, sixteen chemical monomers (
1–16
), including three undescribed oxidative degradation PPAPs (
3–5
), two undescribed PPAPs (
1
and 
2
), four flavonoids (
8–11
), and five phenolic compounds (
12–16
), were discovered from the flowers of 

H. monogynum

. All the compounds were evaluated for COX-2 inhibitory activity, and four flavonoids exhibited excellent activity. These results support the anti-inflammatory effect of flavonoids and illustrate the anti-inflammatory effect of this plant in traditional Chinese medicine. Furthermore, our findings greatly expand the structural diversity of biologically active PPAPs and flavonoids.

The docking study was performed as described previously (
Orlando and Malkowski, 2016
; 
Qin et al., 2020
). For receptor preparation, a 5IKQ human COX-2 model was downloaded from the Protein Database. The complex model of compound 
8
with 5IKQ human COX-2 model was generated by PyMOL Molecular Graphics System. The ligand was bound with 5IKQ at the molecular simulative level by utilizing the Autodock vina 1.1.2. The crystal structure of human COX-2 (PDB code: 5IKQ) was used here for the docking studies (
Qin et al., 2020
). Hydrogen atoms were added and the crystallographic water molecules in 5IKQ were removed. At neutral pH, all the dissociable residues in the system were set to their protonated states. Celecoxib, the inhibitor of COX-2, was used as a reference compound to define the active site of 5IKQ. For further docking, the edited COX-2 and ligand files were transcribed into PDBQT format files. All the parameters were the default.

The cytotoxicity assay was performed as described previously (
Zeng et al., 2021a
).

The MDR reversal activity was performed as described previously (
Zeng et al., 2021a
).
